===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} {{term|hamer|lang=enm}}, {{etyl|ang}} {{term|hamor|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|hamaraz}} (compare Dutch {{term|hamer|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Hammer|lang=de}}, Swedish {{term|hammare|lang=sv}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|aḱmoros}} (compare Sanskrit ''aśmará'' 'stony'{{rfscript|Devanagari|lang=sa}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|h₂ékmōn|title=}} 'stone' (compare Lithuanian {{term|akmuõ|lang=lt}}, Russian {{term|камень|tr=kamen'|lang=ru}}, Serbo-Croatian {{term|kamēn|lang=sh}}, Albanian {{term|kmesë|lang=sq}} 'sickle', Ancient Greek {{term|ἄκμων|tr=akmōn|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}} 'meteor rock, anvil', Avestan {{term||...|tr=asman|lang=ae}}, Sanskrit {{term|अश्मन्|tr=aśman|lang=sa|sc=Deva}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|h₂éḱ-|title=}} 'sharp'. More at [[edge]].
   {{rfscript|Avestan}} <!-- see above, asman -->
